# Cloudflare Pages redirects config.
# Docs: https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/redirects/

# wanderalt.com → wanderalt.app (apex redirect). Cloudflare Pages
# attaches both domains to the same project; this rule fires when the
# host header is the .com. 301 (permanent) so search engines fold the
# domain authority. The :splat catches any path, query, or fragment.
https://wanderalt.com/*    https://wanderalt.app/:splat    301
https://www.wanderalt.com/* https://wanderalt.app/:splat   301

# Force www → apex on the primary domain.
https://www.wanderalt.app/* https://wanderalt.app/:splat   301

# Legacy URL aliases — the old /map and /search lived as standalone
# pages before the May 2026 Discover consolidation. These map to a
# DIFFERENT target (discover.html, one with a query param), so they
# are genuine redirects Cloudflare can't infer on its own. The HTML
# stubs still ship with redirect-on-load JS as a fallback.
/map     /discover.html?view=map    301
/search  /discover.html             301

# NOTE: do NOT add bare-name → *.html rules for /about, /discover,
# /saved, /profile, /curator, /venue, /place. Cloudflare Pages already
# serves pretty URLs natively (it 308-redirects /foo.html → /foo and
# serves /foo as 200). A /discover → /discover.html rule fights that
# canonicalisation and creates an INFINITE redirect loop
# (/discover →301→ /discover.html →308→ /discover → …). The four rules
# that used to live here were removed June 2026 after the loop was
# found on the live preview; verified /curator and /venue (which never
# had rules) already serve 200 on their own.
